<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Gordon Wrinn with the daily news posts</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=214331" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011801.html">Bard Thread</a></B><P>

<I>I've noticed that we have about 15 different bard threads on the front page upset about today's conclusion of the lullaby issue. I am indeed sorry that everyone is upset, however I'll have to ask that you try to avoid making tons of posts on the same subject monopolizing the front page and try to restrict it to a thread or two. Feel free to use this one.<P>

Secondly, I'll have to ask that everyone keep the message board rules in mind when posting, specifically those prohibiting profanity, personal attacks, and flames. There is no idea worth stating that requires the use of any of the above. <P>

Thanks,<P>

-Gordon</I><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

Do you even plan on reading any of these threads? Or do you just want fewer threads so they are easier to lock?<P>

<B>I plan to read this one for now.</B><P>

Why can't you mez level 1 snakes in Freeport?<P>

<B>A player called me on the phone today shortly before I left work. We chatted for a while about various bard-related issues and this is one of them that came up. While he was on the phone I figured I'd check it out. I was unable to reproduce the claim that lullaby works better on level 1 npcs at level 15, than at level 60. In fact, I noticed a substantial decrease in primary resists, though secondaries remained constant, as they should.<P>

In both cases I was able to mez the level one creatures a good percentage of the time.</B><P>

I have a question Abashi. Do you or anyone else read and post to the class forums. Just a thought that maybe this board would not get so flooded if the other boards were given a little feedback.<P>

<B>Not in an official capacity. However, I imagine that some of the designers, programmers, and gms read them from time to time as they are also players of the game. The players will bring their issues to whereever they are most likely to be seen or receive a comment, so I think it's probably better to have it all in one place. I remember back in beta when Brad and team would visit the EQVault boards (all of them), and it usually led to the same posts being cross-posted to all of the boards.</B><P>

If I think you are a company of liars and cheats is that a flame or an opinion?<P>

<B>That would be a flame, and you know it. Please don't make posts of that nature again. A lie requires intent to mislead or deceive as a statement of fact. For instance, "Bards are balanced" is not a lie no matter how much you disagree with it, or how much data you come up with to support your position. It is an opinion. "Alchemy is working" was a mistake. A mistake isn't a lie. "We hope to have it fixed next week." is not a promise to absolutely get it fixed next week, and therefore not a lie if we don't make it.</B><P> 

Are you going to get GZ and Brad on here to explain why they went back on their word? Why they lied to use, then ignored our posts, only to have someone who isn't qualified to test our songs test them?<P>

<B>What word? And what lie? And as far as Ester's qualifications, she's very good at what she does. If you still don't accept that, then I'll also tell you that GZ was involved in the latest round of testing.</B><P>

Make bard Mez as good as necro at least. 25-30 percent resist rates by design are not acceptable.<P>

<B>There is no way that we can make a no-mana song as powerful as a mez as good as a spell that uses mana, which is the reason that it was changed to its current state last August or so.</B><P>

There have been several instances where one of the developers states there is a problem, and then you come along and say it is working as intended. Now I'm not trying to flame, but, as I see it, you are over-riding the programmers and developers. Are you the main person who decides the all of the issues in EQ? <P>

<B>I think that there is little understanding on the level of communications that goes on behind the scenes. Depending on the issue, I may or may not bring other people into the decision process. I was hired due to my understanding of the big picture, being tuned in to what the design team was trying to accomplish. In many cases, I often have a better idea of this than anyone on a large scale, besides of course the producers and lead designers. That is why I make decisions in regard to what issues, for instance, that I'll bring to a tuning meeting for discussion. <P>

Some other things do require a lot of communication between the various members of the team, and it is my responsibility to identify those issues and engage the appropriate people. I translate specific-issue "design speak" into english and see how it fits into the big picture. </B><P>

It seems to me that, lately, you are TRYING to get people mad!!!! <P>

<B>Probably the biggest downside to what I do is that I get to take credit whenever a mistake is made by anyone. That's part of the job. It's not my job to point fingers at individual members, but to accept responsibility for the mistakes on behalf of Verant. <P>

I of course take no joy in being the bearer of bad news. I'd much rather only have to announce the good stuff that pleases everyone, but both components are part of the job. So yes, that means that if a programmer says something that is in error, it may appear that I'm "over-riding" him even though that isn't really the case. I also get to take responsibility for my own mistakes (of which I've made many), and I think that most people here know that I own up to them.</B><P>

Dis-satifaction is 100 times more infectious that satifaction is.<P>

<B>Don't I know it :)</B><P>

Could we see why the effectiveness of a song decreases on mobs as a Bard's level increases? Why do multiple mobs get two resists on a song that has an automatic resist check every 6 seconds anyway? <P>

<B>I think that I've effectively addressed these issues above, but I'll elaborate. The original implementation of the song made it much too powerful considering its lack of a mana control. </B><P>

What is the Vision for Bards use?<P>

<B>That's for you to figure out and establish given the tools that we've provided. What is at your disposal? What can you do? Where can you excel? That is our vision for the bard class.</B><P>

What are the parent classes for Bards?<P>

<B>Bards are not really hybrids despite having the same experience table. They are a class all to their own. If I had to name something, I'd call them part warrior, part rogue, part enchanter, part druid, and part shaman.:)</B><P>

Why are bards one of the least played high level classes?<P>

<B>They are difficult to play well, and their name doesn't scream offensive power like some other classes.</B><P>

Why are dozens of high level bards quitting over this issue?<P>

<B>Dozens of high-level players quit over every issue imaginable. Often I think that in cases like this, the player is burnt out and is looking for a reason to bail out or start a new class.</B><P>

Why am I still holding a flute when playing a drum?<P>

<B>Evidently the drum animations aren't in, or perhaps we don't have anything that looks like a drum when held. I've not personally looked at the appearence in game to see.</B><P>

How was chains imbalancing the game?<P>

<B>Chains had the power to reduce the effective movement of a fleeing NPC to zero, causing it to be an effective root. However, were an actual root spell used, the NPC would have fought having no other option available (fight or flight). It had fleeing mobs at a dead stop, yet not fighting back.</B><P>

What he really wants is a single thread he can ignore instead of having to scroll through pages and pages of threads looking for the "cool" ones he can answer.<P>

<B>No, I just don't want to see one issue monopolizing the front page requiring me to pop around several different threads that say basically the same thing. Hopefully this way I'll be able to post one or two big responses in a place that everyone can find them.</B><P>

You know the ones..."Hey Abashi, what's your favorite color" that seem to get a reply 2 minutes after being posted.<P>

<B>Deep metallic black.</B><P>

Heh gotta love the 'working as intended' standard reply. I just wish VI would finally have GZ write down EXACTLY how each spell is INTENDED to work so that there wont be these ugly surprises months after you start playing a class... It's happened too many times with my enchanter, necro, druid, and ranger...<P>

<B>Most spells work as intended until someone finds a way to make it work in a way that wasn't intended. People think that new way they've discovered is the way it is supposed to work, so when we make changes so that it only works as intended, it's perceived as a nerf.</B><P>

No, they don't plan on reading it. A while ago Abashi posted something saying that 'Class issue were going to still be read, but not replys to anymore.' Raise your hands if you believe that anyone is going to bother reading them.<P>

<B>*raises his hand*<P>

I'll make an exception in this case for a few days since it's on a new and hot issue. </B><P>

Hows this Abashi, the day you start really, really listening to us, and making real changes will be the same day we start listening to you and changing how much negative stuff is on the board.<P>

<B>Please don't confuse "no" with not listening. We always listen, just sometimes the answer isn't the one people want.</B><P>

Why do y'all seem to feel that your inability to mesmerize negates your class? Bards are all-around nifty.<P>

<B>I agree completely.</B><P>

Because we're slowly being nerfed into a manna battery, regen source for other classes.<P>

<B>I wouldn't reduce it to that, but bards are indeed supposed to be a support class.</B><P>

Wouldn't it be easier to just fix the song than to avoid the issue for 10 months, then piss off 80% of your bard community defending yet another unintentional nerf?<P>

<B>There's nothing unintentional about the way that lullaby is currently working. That said, I do indeed wish that we'd done all of the work and announced our findings sooner rather than later. For that, I sincerely apologize.</B><P>

People CAN'T IMAGINE that you want these songs to be this completely useless. Even if it IS as designed, a concept which I myself have a great deal of trouble adjusting to, then your design is broken and needs fixing.<P>

<B>They aren't completely useless, just reduced in usefulness once the targets go over level 30. That said, we're not opposed to revisiting pixie strike and twilight to see if they need to be changed positively now that we know that lullaby is working correctly.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011828.html">Non response bias</a></B><P>

Some people on this board are using the posts of others to show how bad one thing or the other is. How many of us that read these boards and are somewhat happy with what Verant has released. It is time for our voices to be heard. Verant has released a good product. I am not saying that it is perfect because everything has room for improvement. I may just be feeling this way because I am in this profession as well and realize the amount of work that has to go into even some of the littlest of tasks. I just want to encourage everyone who is happy with what is happening with Everquest to start to post. You may start getting more if the programmers feel like the work is appreciated. <P>

<B>Thanks for the note doc, and you are correct in that the programmers enjoy feeling appreciated. I and everyone else wish that players would go on and on about things that please them, but understand that it is not exactly human nature to do so. <P>

We're going to try again this Tuesday, with the implementation of another stunning UI enhancement, the biggest yet, care of Rowyl. I don't want to talk much about it yet until I'm sure that it will make that patch package, but it should be very well received.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

Why no response on these quotes from GZ? <P>

<B>Because the quote really doesn't address the issue at hand. It doesn't say whether he's talking about primary or secondary resists, nor does it say what the level of the target is. Based upon some tests I ran while on the phone with a customer this evening, that quote looks pretty accurate for NPCs under level 30.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011874.html">We need to have 16 memed spells available</a></B><P>

So, the question is why have only 8?<P>

<B>To inject the use of strategy into the spell memorization decision.<P>

It also has the effect of creating risk since you could have the wrong spell lineup ready for an unexpected encounter. Better get someone to watch your back while you remem :)<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011782.html">Abashi, we've had this new proposal, we need an answer.</a></B><P>

I'm one of the several of the high level monks that have explored Kunark rather quickly and we all know that there is no class set armor in Kunark due to balancing issues, most of us agree with you on this, I do as well, I'm proud of what my monk is today. After reading what all my brothers and sisters have to say I must tell you that we feel rather neglected lately. <P>

<B>At some point we are going to have to stop making balance adjustments to classes and focus solely on content development. The problem is that many true problems have been solved over the past 9 months, and this has given the impression that we're out to enhance any class that can form a solid enough backing on the boards.<P>

However, there remains the problem that no matter what we do or what enhancements we make, we'll never be able to get to the point that everyone is happy and doesn't come to the boards here to complain. <P>

At some point, we'd cross a line where half of the people were complaining that the classes were too weak, while the other half would be complaining that they are too strong, and we'd end up upsetting someone any time a change was made.<P>

That point has already been reached. Most of the complaints these days are along the lines of direct class-envy, where one class perceives that they are lesser to another. The problem is that that other class is perfectly happy with that perception. Fixing the first classes issue upsets the second class. <P>

We saw that with warriors and monks in the narrowing of the damage gap from 50 to 60. Monks were happy outdamaging warriors by such a large margin once we put in the hand-to-hand speed bonuses. Warriors were quite upset about that. When we narrowed the gap from 50 to 60, warriors were satiated, and now monks are upset again. We could keep adjusting this gap until both classes are hitting for ice-comet damage every round, and we'd still never get it "quite right" in everyone's eyes.<P>

Regarding your specific topic, I imagine that we could get more creative with the stats on items and create a set of armor. Of course, we have to prioritize between what is needed, and what is wanted. Druids for instance still don't have mid-level quest armor because it isn't needed. The same issue exists with monks and Kunark now.<P>

We are doing one thing though: We're increasing the weight cap on monks in two steps: level 55 and 60. Initially we're testing 4wt at each step.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
